<p> There are two key terms we use to distinguish the groups we collect data from: </p>
<li> <p> The <term> population </term> is the set of all subjects in the study. </p> </li>
<li> <p> A <term> sample </term> is a group or subset of subjects selected from the population. </p> </li>
<p> If we asked ALL residents of the state of Colorado where they were born, then the Colorado residents would be the population. But if we asked just some people from a single city in the state of Colorado, they would a sample from the state. </p>

<p> <em> Checkpoint: </em> At the Denver Zoo, every animal gets a yearly checkup. The new veterinarian selects 20 female animals to determine if they are pregnant in the spring. </p> 
