<p>  There are two main types of data we will be working with: </p>
<p>  <term> Qualitative variables</term>  are placed into distinct categories. Such as the color of cars found in a parking lot. The car colors can be classified as white, red, blue, and black. </p>
<p>  <term> Quantitative variables </term> are numerical and can be ordered. There are two types of quantitative variables. <term> Discrete variables </term> can be counted, such as the number of cars in the different parking lots. The values are whole numbers. Other numerical variables are <term> continuous variables </term> , meaning any value (decimal or fraction) can occur. These are often obtained by measuring something. A continuous variable could be the length of the cars in the parking lot or the time it takes a car to stop when traveling 20 miles per hour. </p>
 



